Slideshow.Advance — Optimization Plan
=====================================

Measured pain
-------------
73 instances, avg 5,557 ms, max 42,881 ms (43 seconds for a single
advance). On a 5s slideshow timer that means the user spends 8x the
intended interval staring at the previous image, then jumps abruptly.

Root cause (from reading code)
------------------------------
advance(windowID:) runs on @MainActor and does, synchronously, in order:
  1. appState.orderedNavigationFiles — DirectoryFilenamePanel.flattenVisible
     of all walkerRoots + a per-element isInScope filter. O(N) tree walk
     on every tick.
  2. ordered.filter { isInScope }  — second O(N) pass.
  3. appState.selectedFile = toPath — triggers didSet:
       - treeNav.revealAncestors(of: path)
       - MCPNotificationBus.shared.emitSelectionChanged
       - WindowState mirror, UserDefaults write.
  4. SwiftUI re-render -> CanvasHost.updateNSView -> ImageCanvasView.setImage,
     which synchronously calls FrameSource.load(url:) and
     NSImage(contentsOfFile:). These can stall many seconds on a big RAW
     or a slow filesystem (network volume, spinning disk, encrypted DMG).
The defer trace measures the synchronous slice of advance(); the 43s
outlier is consistent with the SwiftUI observer chain calling setImage
synchronously inside the same run loop turn before advance returns
(SwiftUI on macOS can re-enter representable updates inline when
@Observable properties are mutated from MainActor).

Design
------
* Add a small prefetch ring inside SlideshowController:
    - prefetchCache: [String: PrefetchEntry] keyed by absolute path,
      capacity 3 (current, +1, +2). LRU evict on insert past cap.
    - PrefetchEntry holds either an in-flight Task<Void, Never> or a
      decoded marker. Decoding happens via FormatLoader.load(url:) on
      a detached Task at .utility QoS — the decoded LoadedImage is
      thrown away after warming the OS file cache and the ImageIO
      decode cache. We do NOT hold pixel buffers (memory risk for
      RAW); the win is paging the file into cache and letting CGImage
      warm up internal caches. (We keep the API black-box: we don't
      reach into FrameSource or the canvas pipeline.)
* On each advance:
    - Compute current files list once (unchanged).
    - Before assigning selectedFile, look up the target path in
      prefetchCache; if entry is .done, advance is effectively free.
      If still in-flight, advance still proceeds (SwiftUI will paint
      when the canvas finishes); the prefetch at least got the bytes
      paged in.
    - After assigning selectedFile, schedule prefetch for the next 1-2
      paths (idx+1, idx+2 with loop wrap) on a background Task. Cancel
      any prefetch task whose path is no longer in the next-2 window
      (user skip / interval flip / wrap).
* Cancellation:
    - Keep currentPrefetchKeys: Set<String>. On each advance, compute
      new keys; cancel tasks for paths in old - new; spawn for new -
      old.
* Memory cap:
    - cache.count <= 3. We are not holding decoded bytes, only the
      "prefetched" status, so memory pressure is bounded.
* Stop / teardown:
    - On stop(windowID:): cancel all prefetch tasks for that window,
      drop the cache entries.
* Timer drift / pause / resume:
    - countdownTimer logic unchanged. nextAdvanceAt + scheduleTick are
      preserved verbatim — prefetch is a side-effect on a separate
      Task and never blocks the timer thread.
* Per-window isolation (multi_window §7.3):
    - prefetch state is keyed by windowID -> per-window struct so two
      windows running independent slideshows don't trample each other.

What stays O(1) on the main thread
----------------------------------
* The synchronous body of advance() still mutates selectedFile and
  scheduleTick. Prefetch dispatch is `Task.detached { ... }` — fire
  and forget. No await inside advance.

Out of scope
------------
* Decoded-image LRU returning ready CGImages to the canvas. That would
  require touching ImageCanvasView / FrameSource (owned by other
  agents). The current design only warms the OS / ImageIO caches via a
  background FormatLoader.load call.
